caption.text:
In the morning of the D-Day, I decided to pick a verse randomly. So 'my finger' led me to the verse in which David sang: This is the day that the Lord has made. We will rejoice and be glad in it. (Psalms 118:24)

I kept saying to myself: Stand back. Stand still. Let God move. And so I believed that whatever was written in my answer sheet was an answer come from God. 
Not many days after the test, as i was reading the Bible, I found a verse in which Jeremiah said, "Nothing is too difficult for Thee." (Jeremiah 32:17) The test might have been too hard for mere humans, but definitely not for God.

In the days of SBMPTN preparation, as I was reading the Bible, I found this powerful verse right when I needed it: "In quietness and confidence shall be your strength." (Isaiah 30:15) It somehow reminded me not to complain how difficult it was. Just, "Be quiet, Suzane, and be confident." People say: Do your best and God will do the rest. Maybe I've used this to strengthen me at one time or another; but not this time. This time, the story of when God told the Israelites to stand back and watch God do His wonders got me. This song was always on my mind: Stand still and let God move.

caption.text: Supporting these 2 wonderful talents beside me. God be with you, Gail and Sarah!

I was spending my lunch time with my friends when my ache was getting much, much worse--it's that time of the month. It was so bad that I felt like passing out. 
When we were done, we got back from the canteen. They found my face so pale and I also lost my balance. So, with the help of my friends, I went to the health center. 
More friends helped me as I was lying helplessly abed. I gotta say their kindness is touching.
Long story short, I went home by taxi. I'd thought things couldn't get more touching, but as I opened my bag to take my phone, I found this paper. Thank you, much love!!
